spanishExample: ¿Cuál es tu edad? ¿Veintitrés?
englishTranslation: What’s your age? Twenty-three?

spanishExample: Acaba de ir al sur con un grupo de veintisiete personas.
englishTranslation: She just went to the south with a group of twenty-seven people.
vocabIncluded: acaba: finishes, he/she/it finishes (Acabar, present, 3rd person)
al: "to the" before a masculine noun

spanishExample: Acabamos de llegar y hay veinticuatro personas en la fila.
englishTranslation: We just got here and there are twenty-four people in the queue.
vocabIncluded: acabamos: finish, we finish (Acabar, present, 1st person plural)
hay: "there is/are" indicating existence (Haber, present, impersonal)

spanishExample: Acaban de ver la película y quieren que yo trate de verla.
englishTranslation: They just watched the movie and they want me to try to watch it.
vocabIncluded: "que", meaning "that" as a conjunction (even in cases where "that" disappears in English)
acaban: finish, they finish (Acabar, present, 3rd person plural)
de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
trate: try, I try (Tratar, subjunctive, 1st person)

spanishExample: Acabas de ir al oeste, ¿ahora quieres ir al norte?
englishTranslation: You just went to the west, now you want to go to the north?
vocabIncluded: acabas: finish, you finish (Acabar, present, 2nd person)
al: "to the" before a masculine noun

spanishExample: Acabo de trabajar, así que no quiero ese puesto.
englishTranslation: I just worked, so I don’t want that position.
vocabIncluded: acabo: finish, I finish (Acabar, present, 1st person)

spanishExample: Acabo de ver una película y se trataba de la guerra.
englishTranslation: I just watched a movie and it was about the war.
vocabIncluded: acabo: finish, I finish (Acabar, present, 1st person)
trataba: tried, he/she/it tried (Tratar, imperfect, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Esa esquina al este tiene veinticinco.
englishTranslation: That corner on the east has twenty-five.
vocabIncluded: al: "to the" before a masculine noun

spanishExample: Estamos tratando de hacerlo, pero se acaban las ideas.
englishTranslation: We’re trying to do it, but the ideas are running out.
vocabIncluded: acaban: finish, they finish (Acabar, present, 3rd person plural)
acabarse: any use of acabar with a reflexive pronoun, changing the meaning to run out)
de used after Tratar to mean “try to”

spanishExample: Esto se acabará, porque solo tenemos veintiuno y no veinticinco.
englishTranslation: This will run out, because we only have twenty-one and not twenty-five.
vocabIncluded: acabarse: any use of acabar with a reflexive pronoun, changing the meaning to run out)
acabará: will finish, he/she/it will finish (Acabar, future, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Ha tratado de conocer a veinticuatro personas en línea.
englishTranslation: She has tried to meet twenty-four people online.
vocabIncluded: "the personal a": using an extra "a" before a direct object when it's a person
de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
ha: "has", "he/she/it has" before a participle (Haber, present, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Hay veintidós personas, entonces no podemos acabar la fiesta.
englishTranslation: There are twenty-two people, so we can’t finish the party.
vocabIncluded: hay: "there is/are" indicating existence (Haber, present, impersonal)

spanishExample: Hay veintiocho o veintinueve personas en ese grupo.
englishTranslation: There are twenty-eight or twenty-nine people in that group.
vocabIncluded: "o": "or" when used between items in a list
hay: "there is/are" indicating existence (Haber, present, impersonal)

spanishExample: Hay veintiséis personas en la fila, tienes que encontrar el centro.
englishTranslation: There are twenty-six people in the queue, you have to find the center.
vocabIncluded: hay: "there is/are" indicating existence (Haber, present, impersonal)
using Tener with "que" to indicate obligation

spanishExample: Mi edad no importa, aunque solo tenga veintidós y no veintitrés.
englishTranslation: My age doesn’t matter, even if I’m only twenty-two and not twenty-three.
vocabIncluded: importa: matters, he/she/it matters (Importar, present, 3rd person)
tener X años: to be X years old (idiom)

spanishExample: No trató de tener el puesto, entonces quiero que trate.
englishTranslation: She didn’t try to have the position, so I want her to try.
vocabIncluded: "que", meaning "that" as a conjunction (even in cases where "that" disappears in English)
de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
trate: try, he/she/it try (Tratar, subjunctive, 3rd person)
trató: tried, he/she/it tried (Tratar, preterite, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Quiero que acabe la línea.
englishTranslation: I want her to finish the line.
vocabIncluded: "que", meaning "that" as a conjunction (even in cases where "that" disappears in English)
acabe: finish, he/she/it finish (Acabar, subjunctive, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Se acabó y ahora está en el frente, al oeste.
englishTranslation: It ended and now she is in the front, to the west.
vocabIncluded: acabarse: any use of acabar with a reflexive pronoun, changing the meaning to run out)
acabó: finished, he/she/it finished (Acabar, preterite, 3rd person)
al: "to the" before a masculine noun

spanishExample: Si vas al norte, la verás en el frente de la calle.
englishTranslation: If you go to the north, you’ll see her in the front of the street.
vocabIncluded: al: "to the" before a masculine noun

spanishExample: Siempre tratan de ir a la vuelta de la esquina.
englishTranslation: They always try to go around the corner.
vocabIncluded: de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
tratan: try, they try (Tratar, present, 3rd person plural)

spanishExample: Trata de hablar, como nosotros tratamos de hacerlo.
englishTranslation: Try to talk, like we’re trying to do it.
vocabIncluded: de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
hablar: to speak / to talk (Hablar infinitive)
tratamos: try, we try (Tratar, present, 1st person plural)

spanishExample: Trata de verlo, pero solo ve veintiocho, no veintinueve.
englishTranslation: She’s trying to see it, but she only sees twenty-eight, not twenty-nine.
vocabIncluded: de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
trata: tries, he/she/it tries (Tratar, present, 3rd person)
ve: sees, he/she/it sees (Ver, present, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Trataba de estar en línea.
englishTranslation: I was trying to be online.
vocabIncluded: de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
trataba: tried, I tried (Tratar, imperfect, 1st person)

spanishExample: Trataba de hablar conmigo antes, pero ya no quiere tratar.
englishTranslation: She used to try to talk to me before, but she doesn’t want to try anymore.
vocabIncluded: de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
hablar: to speak / to talk (Hablar infinitive)
trataba: tried, he/she/it tried (Tratar, imperfect, 3rd person)
ya: adverb meaning "anymore", "already", and a variety of other time-related things

spanishExample: Tratamos de ir hacia el sur, pero no vimos qué línea tomar.
englishTranslation: We tried to go south, but we didn’t see what line to take.
vocabIncluded: "qué" in an implied question, not an actual question
de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
tratamos: tried, we tried (Tratar, preterite, 1st person plural)
vimos: saw, we saw (Ver, preterite, 1st person plural)

spanishExample: Trataré de ir al centro de la ciudad, voy hacia el este.
englishTranslation: I’ll try to go to the city center; I’m going east.
vocabIncluded: al: "to the" before a masculine noun
de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
trataré: will try , I will try (Tratar, future, 1st person)

spanishExample: Traté de hablar con ellos, pero ya acabaron.
englishTranslation: I tried to talk to them, but they already finished.
vocabIncluded: acabaron: finished, they finished (Acabar, preterite, 3rd person plural)
de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
hablar: to speak / to talk (Hablar infinitive)
traté: tried, I tried (Tratar, preterite, 1st person)
ya: adverb meaning "anymore", "already", and a variety of other time-related things

spanishExample: Trato de tener veintiséis, pero solo tengo veintiuno.
englishTranslation: I’m trying to have twenty-six, but I only have twenty-one.
vocabIncluded: de used after Tratar to mean “try to”
trato: try, I try (Tratar, present, 1st person)

spanishExample: Vi veintisiete a la vuelta de la esquina.
englishTranslation: I saw twenty-seven around the corner.
vocabIncluded: vi: saw, I saw (Ver, preterite, 1st person)
